You are familiar with the compartments of the arm from Unit 3. Each compartment of the arm is associated with a dominant movement: muscles of the anterior compartment of the arm flex the elbow, while muscles of the posterior compartment of the arm extend the elbow.

Fortunately for us, trying to learn the relationships between peripheral nerves and movements, all the muscles in each of the two compartments of the arm are innervated by one of the major peripheral nerves derived from the brachial plexus.

The muscles of the anterior compartment of the arm are innervated by the musculocutaneous nerve, and the muscles of the posterior compartment of the arm are innervated by the radial nerve. The axillary nerve innervates the deltoid muscle which clothes the lateral aspect of your shoulder and acts to abduct the glenohumeral joint.
The median and ulnar nerves pass through the anterior compartment of the arm on their way to the forearm and  hand, where they reach their target muscles.
